horthand for defining and understanding Latin American, Latinx, and American experiences of modernity. This close look at the growth of music-making by Latin American and Spanish-speaking musicians in the United States at the turn of the twenty-first century reveals diverging understandings of music’s social and political possibilities for participation and belonging. Through the stories of musicians—Rubén Blades, Shakira, Arturo O’Farrill and the Afro-Latin Jazz Orchestra, and Miguel Zenón—Sounding Latin Music, Hearing the Americas traces how artists use music to produce worlds and senses of the world at the ever-transforming conjunction of Latin America and the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLatin AmericanszUnited StatesxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aLatin Americans-United States-Music-History and criticism. 0aPopular musiczLatin AmericaxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular music-Latin America-History and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aLatin America, Latin music, music and migration, cosmopolitanism, Blackness in the Americas, modernity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226825670423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226825670/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles